<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>🏫 Activity 3 - Modelling First-Order Equations </title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Write solutions to each of the following problems in the space provided. You are encouraged to work in groups, but also encouraged to use your own words to express your ideas. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise workspace="3in">
    <statement>
        <p>
            An <m>LR</m> circuit consists of an inductor with inductance 0.1 Henrys and a resistor with resistance 50 Ohms. 
            
            <ol marker="(i)">
                <li><p> Kirchoff's second law tells us that the net electromotive force around a closed circuit is equal to the total potential drop across all elements of the circuit. </p></li>
                <li><p> Ohm's law tells us that the potential drop across a resistor is <m>V_R = IR</m> where <m>I</m> is the electric current. </p></li>
                <li><p> Similarly, physics informs us that the potential drop across an inductor is <m>V_L = \left(\frac{dI}{dt}\right)L.</m> </p></li>
            </ol>

            A 30V electromotive force is applied to the circuit when the circuit is at rest. Use the information above to model the current <m>I</m> in the circuit at time <m>t</m>. What does your model suggest about the current as <m>t \to \infty</m>? 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            The velocity <m>v(t)</m> at time <m>t</m> of a falling body with mass <m>m</m> can be modelled by the differential equation <md>
                m \frac{dv}{dt} = mg - kv^2.
            </md> where the term <m>mg</m> increases its velocity due to weight and and the term <m>kv^2</m> decreases its velocity due to drag.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <alert>terminal velocity</alert> of an object is the maximum velocity it can reach while falling. Use the differential equation above to find a formula for the object's terminal velocity.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Assuming no air resistance (<m>k=0</m>), solve the differential equation above to find the velocity of the free-falling body. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <alert> terminal velocity </alert> of an object is the maximum velocity it can reach while falling. Find a formula for the terminal velocity using the differential equation above. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your answers from parts (a) and (b) to determine how long an object must fall before achieving terminal velocity. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A skydiver jumps from a plane cruising at an altitude of 20,000 feet. After 25 seconds, he opens his parachute and observes her altitude to be 14,800 feet. Use your model above, together with <m>g \approx 32 \text{ft/s}^2</m>. How fast is the skydiver falling at 15 seconds?  
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
            
  </exercise>


  <exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            After spring break, 100 students came to campus with the flu. Suppose the campus has 8000 students.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The rate at which the disease spreads is proportional to both the number of infected students <m> I </m> and the number of susceptible (uninfected) <m> S </m> students. This can be modeled by the PDE <md> \frac{\partial I}{\partial t} = k I S. </md> Explain why we multiply <m> I,S </m> instead of adding them. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain how we can reduce the PDE model above into the ODE model <md> \frac{dI}{dt} = k I (8000 - I). </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.25in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find appropriate initial conditions for the model. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="2in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the IVP you have built in parts (a)-(c). 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                How many students would you expect to become infected after 10 days? 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Describe the long-term behavior of the flu according to this model. Do your findings sounds true to real life? If not, discuss potential missing factors from the model that could improve its accuracy and write them below. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
